Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":82,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is k